00:08:42,540 --> 00:08:44,010
Let's start with that

176
00:08:44,010 --> 00:08:45,810
and then I'll segue into how to protect it

177
00:08:45,810 --> 00:08:47,010
from yourselves as well.

178
00:08:48,660 --> 00:08:50,940
To understand how we have operationalized

179
00:08:50,940 --> 00:08:54,750
protecting customer
content from AWS operators,

180
00:08:54,750 --> 00:08:57,150
we'll have to step back and understand

181
00:08:57,150 --> 00:08:59,373
how we reimagined virtualization.

182
00:09:01,200 --> 00:09:04,440
On the screen here you
see a representation

183
00:09:04,440 --> 00:09:08,220
of what I would like to
call classic virtualization.

184
00:09:08,220 --> 00:09:11,640
This is still how
virtualization looks like

185
00:09:11,640 --> 00:09:14,520
in most hyperscalers,
in most implementations,

186
00:09:14,520 --> 00:09:16,143
and it works fairly well.

187
00:09:17,010 --> 00:09:18,660
If you look at the picture,
you have these small

188
00:09:18,660 --> 00:09:20,370
white boxes at the top.

189
00:09:20,370 --> 00:09:23,190
They're all customer
instances, they're your VMs.

190
00:09:23,190 --> 00:09:25,650
Then you have these colored
boxes at the bottom.

191
00:09:25,650 --> 00:09:28,590
Let's just say they're all
virtualization functions

192
00:09:28,590 --> 00:09:30,030
that need to happen

193
00:09:30,030 --> 00:09:32,730
to enable the whole virtualization stack.

194
00:09:32,730 --> 00:09:36,060
And between these, you have
a full blown hypervisor.

195
00:09:36,060 --> 00:09:37,860
The Xen hypervisor, which orchestrates

196
00:09:37,860 --> 00:09:40,650
all of these functions,
ring fences the VMs,

197
00:09:40,650 --> 00:09:43,290
allocates the resources and everything.

198
00:09:43,290 --> 00:09:46,320
So now the host, in addition
to providing the VMs,

199
00:09:46,320 --> 00:09:49,590
has to contend with having to take care

200
00:09:49,590 --> 00:09:52,140
of networking and IO functions,

201
00:09:52,140 --> 00:09:54,003
storage and device models,

202
00:09:55,020 --> 00:09:57,510
and other operational functions

203
00:09:57,510 --> 00:10:00,963
like management, security,
monitoring, all of that.

204
00:10:02,070 --> 00:10:06,000
So you can quickly see, in
addition to providing the VMs,

205
00:10:06,000 --> 00:10:07,230
there's a lot of resources

206
00:10:07,230 --> 00:10:09,510
that's getting spent on taking care

207
00:10:09,510 --> 00:10:12,420
of operationalizing these
virtualization functions,

208
00:10:12,420 --> 00:10:14,973
which is all then being
orchestrated by hypervisor.

209
00:10:16,170 --> 00:10:18,900
So when we set out on our
journey to reimagine this,

210
00:10:18,900 --> 00:10:20,400
we challenged the status quo.

211
00:10:20,400 --> 00:10:23,370
It's working well, but can
we do it better, right?

212
00:10:23,370 --> 00:10:26,580
Because we wanted to utilize
the resources on the host

213
00:10:26,580 --> 00:10:29,973
better than we were so we
can provide more VMs to you.

214
00:10:31,590 --> 00:10:33,780
So what we did in that process

215
00:10:33,780 --> 00:10:36,330
was start looking at how can we abstract

216
00:10:36,330 --> 00:10:39,930
these virtualization
functions away from the host.

217
00:10:39,930 --> 00:10:42,820
So we free up more resources from the host

218
00:10:43,920 --> 00:10:45,933
to basically offer more VMs.

219
00:10:47,070 --> 00:10:49,560
So we took each of the functions

220
00:10:49,560 --> 00:10:51,210
that you're seeing at the bottom,

221
00:10:52,230 --> 00:10:55,320
starting with networking and IO functions,

222
00:10:55,320 --> 00:10:57,630
and ran it on custom silicon.

223
00:10:57,630 --> 00:11:00,270
We hardened it and we
ran it on custom silicon

224
00:11:00,270 --> 00:11:02,550
and we abstracted it away from the host

225
00:11:02,550 --> 00:11:04,700
and it went into a
separate box of its own.

226
00:11:05,730 --> 00:11:07,590
We did that first with networking and IO

227
00:11:07,590 --> 00:11:09,976
and we were pretty successful with it.

228
00:11:09,976 --> 00:11:10,809
And we said, okay,

229
00:11:10,809 --> 00:11:13,140
let's go and start
removing piece by piece.

230
00:11:13,140 --> 00:11:16,080
And then we removed
storage and device models.

231
00:11:16,080 --> 00:11:19,740
And finally we came the
to operational functions,

232
00:11:19,740 --> 00:11:22,110
monitoring, management,
security and all that

233
00:11:22,110 --> 00:11:23,160
and removed it.

234
00:11:23,160 --> 00:11:26,970
Each of these was hardened in
its own separate PCIE card.

235
00:11:26,970 --> 00:11:28,773
We call them Nitro cards.

236
00:11:29,670 --> 00:11:33,060
And we have a series of
Nitro cards, which we,

237
00:11:33,060 --> 00:11:35,100
you know, from a mental model perspective,

238
00:11:35,100 --> 00:11:37,350
which we have in a
separate box, if you will,

239
00:11:38,280 --> 00:11:40,860
which implement all of these functions

240
00:11:40,860 --> 00:11:42,990
in tandem with the host.

241
00:11:42,990 --> 00:11:47,403
So we ended up with a
system that looks like this.

242
00:11:49,350 --> 00:11:54,000
By abstracting all of the
virtualization functions away,

243
00:11:54,000 --> 00:11:57,933
we were able to remove
ourselves also from the host.

244
00:11:59,310 --> 00:12:02,160
Now you can quickly see if the
host is just left with VMs,

245
00:12:02,160 --> 00:12:04,050
it doesn't need a full blown hypervisor

246
00:12:04,050 --> 00:12:05,580
like the Xen hypervisor.

247
00:12:05,580 --> 00:12:09,150
So we wrote our own, a very
thin, lightweight hypervisor

248
00:12:09,150 --> 00:12:10,550
called the Nitro hypervisor,

249
00:12:12,570 --> 00:12:14,730
which has very little to do actually.

250
00:12:14,730 --> 00:12:16,350
It just has to ring fence the VMs,

251
00:12:16,350 --> 00:12:18,300
take care of some IO functions,

252
00:12:18,300 --> 00:12:21,420
allocate the right CPU
and memory resources.

253
00:12:21,420 --> 00:12:23,370
It doesn't have to do
all of the orchestration

254
00:12:23,370 --> 00:12:24,870
that the Xen hypervisor had to do.

255
00:12:24,870 --> 00:12:27,303
So it's very lightweight,
very little overhead.

256
00:12:28,500 --> 00:12:30,870
So when we developed
and deployed the system,

257
00:12:30,870 --> 00:12:34,860
in addition to utilizing the
resources of the host better,

258
00:12:34,860 --> 00:12:36,630
we also ended up with a system

259
00:12:36,630 --> 00:12:38,670
