334
00:16:07,290 --> 00:16:10,290
On the screen, what you
see is a 30,000 foot level

335
00:16:10,290 --> 00:16:12,810
of what an EC2 instance would look like.

336
00:16:12,810 --> 00:16:15,180
You have your instance
and within the instance

337
00:16:15,180 --> 00:16:16,650
you have a bunch of different users

338
00:16:16,650 --> 00:16:19,560
who have different levels
of access to the instance.

339
00:16:19,560 --> 00:16:21,240
You have your application

340
00:16:21,240 --> 00:16:23,250
and third party libraries
you perhaps leverage

341
00:16:23,250 --> 00:16:25,200
to build your application.

342
00:16:25,200 --> 00:16:26,403
And then the OS.

343
00:16:27,930 --> 00:16:32,280
Now, if you were to process
sensitive data in this instance,

344
00:16:32,280 --> 00:16:34,020
assuming you had your data encrypted

345
00:16:34,020 --> 00:16:34,980
and stored and everything,

346
00:16:34,980 --> 00:16:38,160
and you're moving it
still encrypted in transit

347
00:16:38,160 --> 00:16:40,110
and bringing it to the instance.

348
00:16:40,110 --> 00:16:42,510
When you encrypted data hits the instance,

349
00:16:42,510 --> 00:16:45,213
if you want to process it,
you have to decrypt it.

350
00:16:46,380 --> 00:16:48,420
That's just how things
work at scale today.

351
00:16:48,420 --> 00:16:51,570
You're gonna have to decrypt
the data inside the instance.

352
00:16:51,570 --> 00:16:54,503
But once you decrypt the
data inside your instance,

353
00:16:54,503 --> 00:16:56,700
you are revealing plain text

354
00:16:56,700 --> 00:16:59,000
to all of the entities
you're seeing in there.

355
00:17:00,210 --> 00:17:02,340
And that's really what you're
looking to protect from

356
00:17:02,340 --> 00:17:04,980
when you're talking about
additional isolation.

357
00:17:04,980 --> 00:17:07,770
And that's when you start
thinking about capabilities

358
00:17:07,770 --> 00:17:09,540
like Nitro Enclaves.

359
00:17:09,540 --> 00:17:13,470
With Nitro Enclaves you have the ability

360
00:17:13,470 --> 00:17:16,230
to allocate CPU and memory resources

361
00:17:16,230 --> 00:17:20,130
from your own EC2 instance to spin up

362
00:17:20,130 --> 00:17:24,210
a hardened and isolated
compute environment

363
00:17:24,210 --> 00:17:25,533
called Nitro Enclaves.

364
00:17:27,570 --> 00:17:32,570
Nitro Enclave has no external
network connectivity.

365
00:17:32,670 --> 00:17:35,040
There is no persistent storage.

366
00:17:35,040 --> 00:17:38,010
There is no administrator
or root user access.

367
00:17:38,010 --> 00:17:42,090
There is no way to SSH into
the enclave by default.

368
00:17:42,090 --> 00:17:44,970
The only communication
channel that exists between,

369
00:17:44,970 --> 00:17:47,370
from the enclave is a secure local channel

370
00:17:47,370 --> 00:17:49,860
between the enclave and
the parent instance.

371
00:17:49,860 --> 00:17:51,000
That's it.

372
00:17:51,000 --> 00:17:51,840
That's the only channel

373
00:17:51,840 --> 00:17:53,580
through which data comes in and goes.

374
00:17:53,580 --> 00:17:56,100
So now if we go back to that
scenario we talked about

375
00:17:56,100 --> 00:17:58,860
where you're bringing encrypted
data into the instance

376
00:17:58,860 --> 00:18:02,250
and you don't want to unpack
that data in the instance,

377
00:18:02,250 --> 00:18:05,490
take that encrypted data
and continue to pipe it

378
00:18:05,490 --> 00:18:09,183
and forward it to the enclave,
still keeping it encrypted.

379
00:18:10,350 --> 00:18:12,390
Once the data hits the enclave,

380
00:18:12,390 --> 00:18:15,690
then proceed to decrypt
it within the enclave,

381
00:18:15,690 --> 00:18:19,020
at which point nobody has
visibility into the data

382
00:18:19,020 --> 00:18:21,150
except the trusted application

383
00:18:21,150 --> 00:18:23,100
that's running inside the enclave,

384
00:18:23,100 --> 00:18:25,300
which can then proceed
to process that data.

385
00:18:26,610 --> 00:18:28,910
And that's how we achieve
additional isolation

386
00:18:29,790 --> 00:18:31,410
and fulfill the requirement

387
00:18:31,410 --> 00:18:34,923
of protecting content
even from yourselves.

388
00:18:39,690 --> 00:18:42,690
Now here's the cool thing,
and in my personal opinion,

389
00:18:42,690 --> 00:18:46,080
this is the coolest feature
that the enclave offers.

390
00:18:46,080 --> 00:18:50,850
Nitro Enclaves can
provide proof of identity.

391
00:18:50,850 --> 00:18:53,580
By doing this, you can be sure

392
00:18:53,580 --> 00:18:56,220
that when you're revealing
secrets to the enclave,

393
00:18:56,220 --> 00:18:58,260
it is the specific enclave

394
00:18:58,260 --> 00:19:01,530
running the expected
and trusted application

395
00:19:01,530 --> 00:19:03,903
to which you are revealing secrets too.

396
00:19:06,300 --> 00:19:08,220
When you decide to spin up an enclave,

397
00:19:08,220 --> 00:19:09,780
you're gonna build an enclave image.

398
00:19:09,780 --> 00:19:11,040
And when you build the enclave image,

399
00:19:11,040 --> 00:19:12,480
you're gonna get a set of measurements,

400
00:19:12,480 --> 00:19:14,043
let's call it a reference hash.

401
00:19:15,030 --> 00:19:18,330
And then when you proceed
to deploy the enclave,

402
00:19:18,330 --> 00:19:19,950
after the enclave has been deployed,

403
00:19:19,950 --> 00:19:22,350
the enclave can fetch
an attestation document

404
00:19:22,350 --> 00:19:24,210
signed by the Nitro hypervisor.

405
00:19:24,210 --> 00:19:28,080
The attestation document
contains computed values

406
00:19:28,080 --> 00:19:30,180
about the enclave that was launched.

407
00:19:30,180 --> 00:19:33,690
It includes information
about the enclave image,

408
00:19:33,690 --> 00:19:35,820
the application in the enclave,

409
00:19:35,820 --> 00:19:39,090
the parent instance ID, IAM roles,

410
00:19:39,090 --> 00:19:40,383
and a few other things.

411
00:19:41,610 --> 00:19:44,193
These are the computed
cryptographic hashes.

412
00:19:45,660 --> 00:19:49,980
So when the enclave wants
to go and access secrets,

413
00:19:49,980 --> 00:19:52,920
what it's gonna do is present
that attestation document

414
00:19:52,920 --> 00:19:55,070
to the entity it's
requesting secrets from.

415
00:19:56,040 --> 00:19:59,070
And that entity is gonna compare
this attestation document

416
00:19:59,070 --> 00:20:00,840
against the reference hash we talked about

417
00:20:00,840 --> 00:20:02,190
when you built the enclave.

418
00:20:03,450 --> 00:20:06,720
And if the values match, that is the proof

419
00:20:06,720 --> 00:20:09,540
the entity needs to make sure

420
00:20:09,540 --> 00:20:12,810
that the enclave has provided
proof of its integrity

421
00:20:12,810 --> 00:20:15,000
and it can now establish
trust with the enclave

422
00:20:15,000 --> 00:20:16,250
to share secrets with it.

423
00:20:17,610 --> 00:20:20,970
This is a high level of
how attestation works.

424
00:20:20,970 --> 00:20:22,500
I'm not gonna get deeper into this

425
00:20:22,500 --> 00:20:24,690
because William's gonna come back later

